        <div class="card-body">
          <h5 class="card-title">Choosing the Right Contraception</h5>
          <p>Finding the right contraceptive method is a personal decision based on several factors:</p>
          
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Effectiveness:</strong> How important is it to avoid pregnancy right now?</li>
            <li><strong>Ease of use:</strong> Will you remember to take a pill daily or prefer a method you don't have to think about?</li>
            <li><strong>Duration:</strong> Do you want short-term or long-term protection?</li>
            <li><strong>Hormonal vs. non-hormonal:</strong> Do you prefer or need to avoid hormones?</li>
            <li><strong>STI protection:</strong> Do you need protection against sexually transmitted infections?</li>
            <li><strong>Side effects:</strong> How might different methods affect your body?</li>
            <li><strong>Future fertility plans:</strong> When do you want to be able to get pregnant, if ever?</li>
            <li><strong>Health factors:</strong> Do you have medical conditions that might affect your options?</li>
          </ul>
          
          <div class="alert alert-info mt-3">
            <p class="mb-0">Discuss these factors with your healthcare provider to find the method that best fits your needs and lifestyle.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="card mb-4">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h5 class="card-title">Common Contraception Myths</h5>
          
          <div class="myth-fact mb-3">
            <p class="fw-bold text-danger">Myth: You can't get pregnant the first time you have sex.</p>
            <p class="fw-bold text-success">Fact: You can get pregnant any time you have unprotected sex, including the first time.</p>
          </div>
          
          <div class="myth-fact mb-3">
            <p class="fw-bold text-danger">Myth: Birth control pills cause infertility.</p>
            <p class="fw-bold text-success">Fact: Fertility returns quickly after stopping most contraceptive methods, including the pill.</p>
          </div>
          
          <div class="myth-fact mb-3">
            <p class="fw-bold text-danger">Myth: IUDs are only for women who have had children.</p>
            <p class="fw-bold text-success">Fact: IUDs are safe and effective for most women, regardless of whether they've had children.</p>
          </div>
          
          <div class="myth-fact mb-3">
            <p class="fw-bold text-danger">Myth: Withdrawal ("pulling out") is highly effective.</p>
            <p class="fw-bold text-success">Fact: Withdrawal has a relatively high failure rate (22% with typical use) and offers no STI protection.</p>
          </div>
          
          <div class="myth-fact">
            <p class="fw-bold text-danger">Myth: You don't need contraception during breastfeeding.</p>
            <p class="fw-bold text-success">Fact: While exclusive breastfeeding can provide some protection in the first 6 months postpartum, it's not reliable contraception.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="card mb-4">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h5 class="card-title">Fertility Awareness</h5>
          
          <p>Understanding your fertile window is valuable whether you're trying to prevent or achieve pregnancy. A woman is typically fertile for about 6 days each cycle:</p>
          
          <ul>
            <li>The 5 days before ovulation</li>
            <li>The day of ovulation itself</li>
          </ul>
          
          <p>Signs of fertility include:</p>
          
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Cervical mucus changes:</strong> Becomes clear, slippery, and stretchy (like egg white) during fertile days</li>
            <li><strong>Basal body temperature rise:</strong> Slight increase (0.4-1.0Â°F) after ovulation</li>
            <li><strong>Ovulation predictor kits:</strong> Detect the luteinizing hormone (LH) surge before ovulation</li>
            <li><strong>Cycle tracking:</strong> Calendar-based prediction of fertile days</li>
          </ul>
          
          <div class="text-center mt-3">
            <a href="<%= url_for('ovulation_fertility') %>" class="btn btn-primary">Learn More About Fertility Tracking</a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="card mb-4">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h5 class="card-title">Planning for Pregnancy</h5>
          
          <p>If you're considering pregnancy in the future, these steps can help optimize health for both you and your future baby:</p>
          
          <h6 class="mt-3">3+ Months Before Conception:</h6>
          <ul>
            <li>Begin taking prenatal vitamins with folic acid (400-800 mcg daily)</li>
            <li>Have a preconception check-up</li>
            <li>Update vaccinations</li>
            <li>Review medications with your healthcare provider</li>
            <li>Manage chronic health conditions</li>
            <li>Achieve a healthy weight</li>
            <li>Quit smoking and avoid alcohol</li>
            <li>Begin tracking your menstrual cycle</li>
          </ul>
          
          <h6 class="mt-3">When You're Ready to Conceive:</h6>
          <ul>
            <li>Time intercourse during your fertile window</li>
            <li>Maintain a healthy lifestyle with balanced nutrition</li>
            <li>Manage stress</li>
            <li>Limit caffeine intake</li>
            <li>Avoid environmental toxins</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="text-center mt-3">
            <a href="<%= url_for('pregnancy_milestones') %>" class="btn btn-outline-primary">Pregnancy Milestone Tracking</a>
          </div>
        </div>
